19:28.133 --> 19:29.701
is a 2.6 ROAS.

19:29.701 --> 19:31.270
And it's a 3.7 on Amazon.

19:31.270 --> 19:32.571
What do you
sell that for?

19:32.571 --> 19:33.972
$29.99 for both games.

19:33.972 --> 19:35.107
-Wow.
-Wow.

19:35.107 --> 19:36.441
So you've got to be making
a boatload of money.

19:36.441 --> 19:37.509
-Yeah.
-I am.

19:37.509 --> 19:39.545
[ Laughter ]

19:39.545 --> 19:42.748
Okay.
So, my net margin is at 25%.

19:42.748 --> 19:45.350
But last month, it was at 32%.

19:45.350 --> 19:47.653
So you'll make over
$1 million this year

19:47.653 --> 19:48.921
if you just
continue your sales.

19:48.921 --> 19:53.792
Yeah. This year, I will make
$1.25 million in profit.

19:55.194 --> 19:57.062
Thank you, Mark.
Corcoran: Wow.

19:57.062 --> 19:58.830
Tell me,
why do you need a Shark?

19:58.830 --> 20:03.368
Why I want a Shark is for
two very important reasons.

20:03.368 --> 20:05.003
I want product expansion.

20:05.003 --> 20:06.805
So, how I view this

20:06.805 --> 20:08.840
is basically,
from pre-K to grade six,

20:08.840 --> 20:10.509
I want to create
a reading funnel

20:10.509 --> 20:13.745
where I take kids through
their entire literacy journey.

20:13.745 --> 20:15.647
And then I want to go
into gamifying

20:15.647 --> 20:17.082
other parts of the curriculum.

20:17.082 --> 20:19.117
I want to go
international expansion.

20:19.117 --> 20:21.286
I want to translate
to other languages.

20:21.286 --> 20:22.621
I also want to go into

20:22.621 --> 20:24.423
the English as a second language
market.

20:24.423 --> 20:27.159
Why would you need a Shark
to do those items, though?

20:27.159 --> 20:30.762
Okay, because I feel like
to go from where I am right now

20:30.762 --> 20:32.030
to where I want to go,

20:32.030 --> 20:33.899
to be a $50-billion,
$100-billion --

20:33.899 --> 20:35.334
Or a hundred --
"Billion."

20:35.334 --> 20:36.902
Million-dollar company...
[ Laughs ]

20:36.902 --> 20:39.071
I want to focus
on the creative side.

20:39.071 --> 20:41.773
Like, I'm working 13-hour days.
I haven't taken a weekend off.

20:41.773 --> 20:43.542
You always will, by the way.
Don't dream about that.

20:43.542 --> 20:45.544
And that's fine. I love it.
I love what I do.

20:45.544 --> 20:48.380
But I would love to be focused
on the creative aspect of it.

20:48.380 --> 20:50.449
And for a Shark to --
I'm not saying you guys

20:50.449 --> 20:52.851
are going to be doing
the work for me at all,

20:52.851 --> 20:56.622
but basically that you could --
you could help mentor me.

20:56.622 --> 20:59.324
Who's the right people to hire?
What's the next step for this?

20:59.324 --> 21:02.961
I'd like to make you
an offer if I may, alright?

21:02.961 --> 21:07.633
The 10% for $500,000 just
doesn't feel to me about right.

21:07.633 --> 21:08.500
Okay?
Mm-hmm.

21:08.500 --> 21:09.735
I'll give you

21:09.735 --> 21:12.004
$500,000 for 20%.

21:12.004 --> 21:14.506
I would be very happy
at 20%, honestly.

21:14.506 --> 21:16.108
[ Laughter ]
Barbara...

21:16.108 --> 21:18.277
That's like getting all your
money back on day one, Barbara.

21:18.277 --> 21:20.746
Brandi: I love you. I can't tell
you how much I love you.

21:20.746 --> 21:22.080
She's your
right partner.

21:22.080 --> 21:24.049
You are definitely
my right partner.

21:24.049 --> 21:26.718
But what are you
thinking? "But..."

21:26.718 --> 21:29.154
Can we go to 15%?

21:29.154 --> 21:31.023
Yes, we can.
Do we have a deal?

21:32.724 --> 21:34.259
We have a deal.
Okay.

21:34.259 --> 21:36.828
[ Laughter ]
John: Wow.

21:36.828 --> 21:40.165
I am your poster baby for this.
What an incredible story.

21:40.165 --> 21:43.135
We are gonna make
the smart kids so jealous.

21:43.135 --> 21:45.103
I love you.
Thank you, Barbara.

21:45.103 --> 21:46.305
Bye, guys.
Thank you so much.

21:46.305 --> 21:47.506
Cuban:
Congratulations, Brandi.

21:47.506 --> 21:48.840
Good job, Barb.
Corcoran: Thank you.

21:48.840 --> 21:50.809
Well done.
Right up my alley!

21:50.809 --> 21:52.644
Brandi: [ Exhales deeply ]
I feel such an affinity

21:52.644 --> 21:55.881
with Barbara because, you know,
she worked through her life

21:55.881 --> 21:57.549
as a waitress
to get to where she was.

21:57.549 --> 21:59.418
She came from
a very middle-class family.

21:59.418 --> 22:02.020
I feel so aligned
with how hardworking she is

22:02.020 --> 22:04.089
and dedicated
and determined she is,

22:04.089 --> 22:07.125
and it feels like
a perfect partnership.

22:07.125 --> 22:12.431
♪♪

22:12.431 --> 22:14.533
You wanna pull
it up to your chest.
You may wanna
go back on the -- Yeah.

22:14.533 --> 22:16.401
-Now, Robert, start hopping.
-So it fits...

22:16.401 --> 22:17.402
It is. Yes.

22:17.402 --> 22:18.704
We don't advise
to do that.

22:18.704 --> 22:20.339
Yes, 'cause we don't
want you to fall.

22:20.339 --> 22:23.742
Look. Being a Shark
is all about the commitment.

22:23.742 --> 22:25.911
I've even bled on this set.

22:25.911 --> 22:29.047
[ Laughter ]

22:29.047 --> 22:30.382
You okay, Robert?

22:30.382 --> 22:31.616
[ Whimpering ] I'm okay.

22:31.616 --> 22:32.851
That definitely normally
doesn't happen.

22:32.851 --> 22:33.752
Ohh!
[ Laughter ]

22:33.752 --> 22:35.187
See what we have
to deal with?

22:35.187 --> 22:37.489
Oh, my God!
I'm bleeding!
[ Sighs ] Hey.

22:37.489 --> 22:39.658
Greiner: [Laughing]
Oh, my God!
Cuban: Robert
is bleeding.

22:39.658 --> 22:40.692
Robert, are you okay?
I hate you!

22:40.692 --> 22:41.860
Kupper: Oh, no!

22:41.860 --> 22:43.762
I think Kevin pushed me,
honestly.

22:43.762 --> 22:45.997
I'm bleeding, people!

22:45.997 --> 22:48.500
Get a lawyer.
[ Chuckles ]

22:51.269 --> 22:55.273
♪♪

22:55.273 --> 22:57.309
Narrator:
Next up is a high-tech way

22:57.309 --> 22:59.778
to stay connected on the slopes.

22:59.778 --> 23:08.220
♪♪

23:08.220 --> 23:10.188
Hey, Sharks.
My name is Fletcher.

23:10.188 --> 23:12.457
And these are my brothers,
David and Henry.

23:12.457 --> 23:14.292
And we're
the Rekkie team.

23:14.292 --> 23:17.062
Today we're seeking
a $300,000 investment

23:17.062 --> 23:20.232
in exchange for 10% equity
in our company, Rekkie.

23:20.232 --> 23:22.401
The three of us
grew up skiing together,

23:22.401 --> 23:24.035
and we still believe
there's nothing better

23:24.035 --> 23:26.037
than the perfect day
on the mountain,

23:26.037 --> 23:28.340
catching that first chairlift
up in the morning

23:28.340 --> 23:30.409
and cruising
all day long.

23:30.409 --> 23:33.345
The problem --
when we get split up!

23:33.345 --> 23:35.680
Well, losing this guy
happens a lot.

23:35.680 --> 23:38.750
Look. I'm the middle child.
I have to be different.

23:38.750 --> 23:41.853
While these two skiers race
each other down icy cruisers,

23:41.853 --> 23:43.388
I'm peeling off
with my snowboard

23:43.388 --> 23:45.991
to find fresh powder and my
own way down the mountain.

23:45.991 --> 23:47.726
That's all well and good,
Fletch,

23:47.726 --> 23:49.528
until we get to the bottom
of the chairlift

23:49.528 --> 23:51.163
and don't know
which way you went.

23:51.163 --> 23:53.765
Sharks, this happens
all the time.

23:53.765 --> 23:55.867
And he could try
to text us or call us,

23:55.867 --> 23:57.836
but it's hard
to whip out your phone

23:57.836 --> 23:59.604
in the middle
of a ski run.

23:59.604 --> 24:01.239
We knew there had to be
a better way,

24:01.239 --> 24:03.708
so we created it --
with Rekkie.

24:03.708 --> 24:05.577
Rekkies are
smart snow goggles

24:05.577 --> 24:07.546
with a built-in
heads-up display.

24:07.546 --> 24:09.981
The display projects
directly onto the lens

24:09.981 --> 24:12.918
and just seems to float
out in front of your forehead.

24:12.918 --> 24:14.386
With just
a quick glance up,

24:14.386 --> 24:16.021
you can see where
your friends are,

24:16.021 --> 24:18.757
how fast you're going,
read your unread texts,

24:18.757 --> 24:22.427
control your music, answer
phone calls, and so much more.

24:22.427 --> 24:26.131
But these aren't VR goggles.
We're not blocking your view.

24:26.131 --> 24:27.699
In fact, we're using
state of the art

24:27.699 --> 24:29.668
in lens clarity,
anti-fog,

24:29.668 --> 24:31.803
and contrast-boosting
technologies

24:31.803 --> 24:34.539
to make them the best
ski goggles possible.

24:34.539 --> 24:36.441
And that's before
you even turn them on.

24:36.441 --> 24:39.277
Sharks, it's time to grab
your skis or your snowboard

24:39.277 --> 24:40.779
and join us
on the mountain.

24:40.779 --> 24:44.149
We know with your help we can
take Rekkie to the next level.

24:44.149 --> 24:45.717
Before we get
into the business,

24:45.717 --> 24:47.452
Henry's gonna walk you guys
through a demo

24:47.452 --> 24:49.287
and show you
how the goggles work.
Okay.

24:49.287 --> 24:52.023
So, I rigged up a camera
inside this helmet

24:52.023 --> 24:54.092
so you can see
exactly how it looks

24:54.092 --> 24:56.428
when you're wearing
Rekkie goggles.

24:56.428 --> 24:58.263
The default display
is the dashboard,

24:58.263 --> 25:01.566
which has your speed,
elevation, a clock,

25:01.566 --> 25:04.035
number of new notifications
in that top left,

25:04.035 --> 25:05.770
and, of course,
the compass.

25:05.770 --> 25:07.873
Alright, Sharks, you each
have a set of goggles

25:07.873 --> 25:08.974
out in front of you.

25:08.974 --> 25:11.243
Feel free
to try them on.

25:11.243 --> 25:13.812
♪♪

25:13.812 --> 25:15.013
Now, these are cool.

25:15.013 --> 25:17.349
Let's say you're coming
down the mountain.

25:17.349 --> 25:20.085
Fletcher goes off like crazy
to the right.

25:20.085 --> 25:23.388
I don't understand how that
helps me find somebody.

25:23.388 --> 25:25.991
You are in a group of friends
on our app,

25:25.991 --> 25:29.060
and you can either just
have the app on your phone

25:29.060 --> 25:31.763
so it's tracking where
the phone's GPS location.

25:31.763 --> 25:34.699
Or if you're in an area,
say, with low cell service

25:34.699 --> 25:36.535
like out in
the back country,

25:36.535 --> 25:40.338
the goggles themselves have
a built-in long-range radio,

25:40.338 --> 25:42.474
so you can still know
where your friends are

25:42.474 --> 25:44.309
even if you don't have
cell service.

25:44.309 --> 25:47.145
The app's really easy to use.
You create a ski group.

25:47.145 --> 25:49.214
You can see where
your friends are on a map,

25:49.214 --> 25:50.615
you pair your goggles,

25:50.615 --> 25:52.017
and then you can also
track your stats.

25:52.017 --> 25:54.653
But the friend is tagged
by their cell number?

25:54.653 --> 25:56.321
By their cellphone.
Okay.

25:56.321 --> 25:58.123
For me --
and I ski a lot --

25:58.123 --> 26:00.625
my biggest problem
is finding my friends.

26:00.625 --> 26:03.528
It wouldn't help me so much
to know their distance from me,

26:03.528 --> 26:06.831
but I need to know
the name of the run

26:06.831 --> 26:10.402
and the chair that feeds that
run. Does this show this?

26:10.402 --> 26:12.270
-We're working on that.
-Ah. That's everything.

26:12.270 --> 26:14.205
That'll be hopefully coming
in a software update.

26:14.205 --> 26:16.274
But you can see --
If you do have time

26:16.274 --> 26:17.509
to pull out your phone --

26:17.509 --> 26:19.177
Say you're on a chairlift
or the gondola,

26:19.177 --> 26:21.379
you can see on the maps tab
of the app

26:21.379 --> 26:23.648
exactly the name
of the run they're on.

26:23.648 --> 26:25.016
But you still have to
pull out your phone.

26:25.016 --> 26:26.651
John: Yeah, but aren't you
back to stage one again,

26:26.651 --> 26:28.587
pulling out your phone?

26:30.388 --> 26:33.124
What does this cost and what
does it cost you to make it?

26:33.124 --> 26:35.126
And how many years
have you been selling it?

26:35.126 --> 26:37.195
So, we just launched
late last year,

26:37.195 --> 26:39.331
so we have one ski season
under our belts.

26:39.331 --> 26:42.000
So far, we've done
about $175,000 in sales.

26:42.000 --> 26:43.802
-Good for you.
-Great. How did you sell it?

26:43.802 --> 26:45.170
Through the ski shops?

26:45.170 --> 26:46.805
-All direct-to-consumer.
-Wow.

26:46.805 --> 26:47.872
Price point?

26:47.872 --> 26:48.974
It's $349.
O'Leary: $349?

26:48.974 --> 26:50.508
What does it cost you
to make it?

26:50.508 --> 26:52.877
So, during the pandemic,
chip prices spiked.

26:52.877 --> 26:54.479
Things got a little expensive.

26:54.479 --> 26:55.647
We were at $160...

26:55.647 --> 26:56.881
Mm-hmm.
...per unit.

26:56.881 --> 26:58.516
Our current run that's
in production right now

26:58.516 --> 27:00.051
is $130 a unit.

27:00.051 --> 27:02.754
And we think with some scale,
given the nature of the product,

27:02.754 --> 27:05.523
we can get that down
to about $100 landed.
That's our goal.

27:05.523 --> 27:07.258
How does $349 compare

27:07.258 --> 27:10.462
to the cost of a typical
good ski goggle?

27:10.462 --> 27:11.830
Same general ballpark.

27:11.830 --> 27:13.598
So, like, the top brands
usually have something

27:13.598 --> 27:15.834
that's in kind of
the low $300s.

27:15.834 --> 27:18.303
We believe this is the best
ski goggle on the market,

27:18.303 --> 27:19.838
even without the display.

27:19.838 --> 27:23.041
Is there other people
anywhere close to doing this

27:23.041 --> 27:24.743
right now
in your market?

27:24.743 --> 27:26.344
No, not really.
No.

27:26.344 --> 27:28.279
There are some people
in some other sports.

27:28.279 --> 27:30.348
Rekkie is about
action sports.

27:30.348 --> 27:34.219
We think this is practical,
really cool augmented reality

27:34.219 --> 27:35.487
for action sports.

27:35.487 --> 27:36.821
Is this patented?

27:36.821 --> 27:40.158
So, we do have a patent pending
on the -- on the display

27:40.158 --> 27:41.993
and the way
that the display reflects

27:41.993 --> 27:44.829
off of the curved lens
of the goggle.
Right.

27:44.829 --> 27:47.198
So, guys,
who's the tech dweeb?

27:47.198 --> 27:48.900
Greiner: Yeah.
So, Henry's
the hardware...

27:48.900 --> 27:50.568
What's your background,
Henry?

27:50.568 --> 27:53.972
So, I got a mechanical
and aerospace engineering degree

27:53.972 --> 27:55.473
from Princeton then --

27:55.473 --> 27:56.608
Whew!
Oh, that's nothing!

27:56.608 --> 27:57.809
Wow.
[ Laughs ]

27:57.809 --> 28:00.745
Then I worked
in Silicon Valley

28:00.745 --> 28:03.381
as a research engineer
for a car company.

28:03.381 --> 28:04.649
And what about you guys?

28:04.649 --> 28:06.317
So, our backgrounds
are in business.

28:06.317 --> 28:09.020
David started his career
in management consulting

28:09.020 --> 28:10.822
then went into
private equity.

28:10.822 --> 28:12.557
I was in investment banking
in New York

28:12.557 --> 28:14.059
and then went into
private equity, as well.

28:14.059 --> 28:16.561
So you guys went out and raised
how much money for Henry?

28:16.561 --> 28:17.562
Between
the co-founders,

28:17.562 --> 28:18.663
we're fully bootstrapped
to date.

28:18.663 --> 28:20.065
-Oh, wow. Good for you.
-Unusual.

28:20.065 --> 28:22.834
And we've put in $200,000
of our own hard-earned money.

28:22.834 --> 28:24.335
That's it?
Just 200 grand?

28:24.335 --> 28:25.904
Greiner: Wow.
Good for you.

28:25.904 --> 28:29.541
And we also won a $40,000 grant
from a local firm...

28:29.541 --> 28:31.743
-You haven't taken any money?
-Good for you guys. Amazing.

28:31.743 --> 28:33.144
That seems so cheap, right?
It is.

28:33.144 --> 28:34.879
We have not raised
any outside capital

28:34.879 --> 28:36.481
or given
any equity away.

28:36.481 --> 28:39.317
Okay. Are you full-time
running the business now?

